[1
Date: Thu, 06 May 1999 13:22:06 -0400
From: "Marjorie P. Pollack" <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: WHO/CSR reports, Thu 06 May 1999

Disease outbreaks reported
6 May 1999

Marburg disease in Democratic Republic of Congo - Update 2
---------------------------------------------------------------
Marburg virus has been confirmed as the cause of the viral haemorrhagic
fever in the Watsa zone, in the northeastern part of the country. Latest
figures are an estimated 76 cases with 52 deaths.
Laboratory and epidemiological experts from WHO Headquarters are
joining the WHO/Medecins sans frontieres (Belgium and the Netherlands)
team already in the area.
Main tasks will be to determine the current size of the outbreak and the
source of the virus. Technical assistance will also be given to further
implement control measures.
Marburg disease is not very well known; it has caused one past outbreak and
several sporadic cases. It is transmitted to people following contact with
infected animals and animal tissues, and from person-to-person from close
contact with infected patients and body fluids. Both Marburg and the
closely related Ebola virus are often characterized by the sudden onset of
fever, malaise, muscle pain, headache and conjunctivitis. This is followed
by sore throat, vomiting, diarrhoea, rash, and both internal and external
bleeding. Liver function may be abnormal and platelet function may be
impaired.
No specific treatment or vaccine exists for Marburg disease. Severe cases
require intensive supportive care, as patients are frequently dehydrated
and in need of intravenous fluids. Experimental studies involving the use
of hyperimmune sera on animals demonstrated no long-term protection
against the disease after interruption of therapy.
Suspected cases should be isolated from other patients and strict barrier
nursing techniques practised. All hospital personnel should be briefed on
the nature of the disease and its routes of transmission. Particular
emphasis should be placed on ensuring that high-risk procedures such as the
placing of intravenous lines and the handling of blood, secretions,
catheters and suction devices are done under barrier nursing conditions.
Hospital staff should have individual gowns, gloves and masks. Gloves and
masks must not be reused unless disinfected. Patients who die from the
disease should be promptly buried or cremated.
The natural reservoir of the Marburg virus is unknown. Ebola and Marburg
are viruses from the filovirus family.
