[3
Date: Thu 06 May 1999 13:34:51 -0400
From: "Marjorie P. Pollack" <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Reuters, Thu 6 May 1999

The World Health Organisation (WHO) said on Thursday a virus
responsible for 63 deaths in the Democratic Republic of the Congo was
not Ebola, but a related haemorrhagic fever probably transmitted by
bats or rats.
The WHO has recorded 63 deaths from 68 cases of the disease, while
Congolese state television has reported 72 have died out of 76 registered
cases.
"In all likelihood the reservoir (for the virus) was either rats or
bats,'' Hartl said. "We are sending animal specialists to find the rats
and bats in the old abandoned gold mines and trap and test them.''
